6. Why does this work?

The stack always stores prices in decreasing order.

Whenever a new price is greater than or equal to the top price,

That older price can never affect future spans again.

So we:

Pop it.

Add its span to the current span.


Each price is:

pushed once

popped once


This makes the algorithm O(n) overall.


---

7. Java Code

class StockSpanner {

    Stack<int[]> stack;

    public StockSpanner() {
        stack = new Stack<>();
    }

    public int next(int price) {

        int span = 1;

        while (!stack.isEmpty() && stack.peek()[0] <= price) {
            span += stack.pop()[1];
        }

        stack.push(new int[]{price, span});

        return span;
    }
}


---

8. Time Complexity

Amortized O(1) per next() call.

Overall, for n calls:

O(n)

Each price is pushed and popped at most once.


---

9. Space Complexity

O(n)

In the worst case (strictly decreasing prices), all prices remain in the stack.


---

10. Important Interview Note

Unlike Next Greater Element and Daily Temperatures, this problem is online—prices arrive one at a time.

Instead of storing only prices, store (price, span) pairs.

When popping smaller or equal prices, add their spans to the current span instead of recounting previous days.

This is another classic application of a Monotonic Decreasing Stack.


---

11. One-line Note for Interviews

Use a Monotonic Decreasing Stack storing (price, span) pairs. Pop all smaller or equal prices, add their spans to the current span, then push the current price with its total span. 🚀
